          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Intelligent Tutoring System",
          "Correct Answer in Next Question",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "ASSIST2009: 4,217; Algebra2005: 574; NIPS34: 4,918; EdNet: 4,999",
          "Mathematics / Algebra / English tutoring datasets",
          "ASSIST2009, Algebra2005, NIPS34, EdNet",
          "Chronologically ordered interaction sequences with question, KC set, response, and timestamp; question embeddings; concept embeddings; question-level and concept-level interaction encodings",
          "Existing deep sequential KT models struggle to model individual question information, especially for less interactive questions, which can cause overfitting of question embeddings. They also lack sufficiently interpretable prediction results for teachers",
          "Q-MCKT explicitly models student knowledge acquisition at both question and concept levels, uses mixture of experts for more robust knowledge acquisition states, adds fine-grained question-centric contrastive learning for less interactive questions, and uses an IRT-based interpretable prediction layer",
          "Followed the preprocessing protocol in pyKT: removed student sequences shorter than 3 attempts; maximum input sequence length 200; five-fold cross-validation; within each fold, 80% of student sequences used for training/validation and 20% for evaluation; trained up to 200 epochs with early stopping and Adam; hyperparameters searched with Bayesian optimization",
          "DKT, DKT+, DKT-F, DKVMN, ATKT, GKT, SAKT, SAINT, AKT, SKVMN, DeepIRT, qDKT, AT-DKT, SimpleKT, Q-MCKT",
          "5-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "AST09: \n{AUC: 0.7876 - MCKT, Accuracy: 0.7376 - MCKT}\n\nAlgebra05: \n{AUC: 0.9035 - MCKT, Accuracy: 0.8239 - MCKT}\n\nNIPS34:\n{AUC: 0.8035 - MCKT, Accuracy: 0.7329 - MCKT}\n\nEdNet: \n{AUC: 0.7228 - MCKT, Accuracy: 0.7067 - MCKT}\n\n",
          "Strong KT paper with a clear dual emphasis on accuracy and interpretability. The visualizations on pages 22–23 show both concept-level knowledge-state evolution and how the final prediction is decomposed into interpretable question and concept acquisition scores",
          "More complex than standard KT baselines; interpretability is at the prediction-result level rather than full model transparency; benefits of contrastive learning are smaller on datasets with low average interactions per question\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
